 :tx/provenance :observed
 :tx/rationale "DOG-FOOD SESSION 026 — DEEPER ANALYSIS. The fundamental tension I experience: braid is EXCELLENT for structured knowledge capture (observe, harvest, seed) but POOR for structured knowledge RETRIEVAL during active work. Specifics: (A) CAPTURE is frictionless: braid observe captures an insight in one command. braid task create with rich descriptions works. braid write assert sets arbitrary attributes. The store grows monotonically and nothing is lost. This is the core promise of DDIS working. (B) RETRIEVAL during work is painful: I cannot find my own tasks without Datalog. braid task list truncates. braid task ready shows 271 tasks with no filtering. No full-text search across tasks. No braid task list --grep pattern. No braid task list --created-today. The store has the data but the CLI doesn't surface it efficiently. (C) The BATCH WORKFLOW is unoptimized: Creating 27 tasks required 27 separate braid task create commands, 17 dep add commands, ~15 write assert commands. Each takes ~2 seconds (cargo run overhead). Total: ~2 minutes of pure CLI execution. A braid task create-batch accepting a structured file (YAML/EDN) would be 10x faster. (D) The VERIFICATION WORKFLOW is good: braid query with Datalog lets me audit anything. The store IS the source of truth. I can verify dep edges, check attributes, count results. This is the payoff of C7 (self-bootstrap) — the system can inspect itself. (E) The SEED is genuinely useful: braid seed --task topology showed me relevant spec elements, recent observations, and session history. It IS a compressed knowledge projection. The L0/L1/L2/L3 pyramid would make it even better."
